06084nam a22008655i 9780812204322DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979748410  a97808122043227 a10.9783/97808122043222doi  a(DE-B1597)449343  a(OCoLC)794700594  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBV4030b.C53 2011 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a230.071/1732221 aClark, Elizabeth A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFounding the Fathers :bEarly Church History and Protestant Professors in Nineteenth-Century America /cElizabeth A. Clark. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (576 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDivinations: Rereading Late Ancient Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Higher Education and Religion in Nineteenth-Century United States -- tPart I. The Setting: Contextualizing the Study of Early Christianity in America -- tChapter 1. The Institutions and the Professors -- tChapter 2. Infrastructure: Teaching, Textbooks, Primary Sources, and Libraries -- tPart II. History and Historiography -- tChapter 3 Defending the Faith: European Theories and American Professors -- tChapter 4. History and Church History -- tChapter 5 Development and Decline: Challenges to Historiographical Categories -- tPart III. Topics of Early Christian History in Nineteenth-Century Analysis -- tChapter 6. Polity and Practice -- tChapter 7. Roman Catholicism -- tChapter 8. Asceticism, Marriage, Women, and the Family -- tChapter 9. The Uses of Augustine -- tAppendix: Student Notetakers -- tAbbreviations and Archival Sources -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThrough their teaching of early Christian history and theology, Elizabeth A. Clark contends, Princeton Theological Seminary, Harvard Divinity School, Yale Divinity School, and Union Theological Seminary functioned as America's closest equivalents to graduate schools in the humanities during the nineteenth century. These four Protestant institutions, founded to train clergy, later became the cradles for the nonsectarian study of religion at secular colleges and universities. Clark, one of the world's most eminent scholars of early Christianity, explores this development in Founding the Fathers: Early Church History and Protestant Professors in Nineteenth-Century America.Based on voluminous archival materials, the book charts how American theologians traveled to Europe to study in Germany and confronted intellectual currents that were invigorating but potentially threatening to their faith. The Union and Yale professors in particular struggled to tame German biblical and philosophical criticism to fit American evangelical convictions. German models that encouraged a positive view of early and medieval Christianity collided with Protestant assumptions that the church had declined grievously between the Apostolic and Reformation eras. Trying to reconcile these views, the Americans came to offer some counterbalance to traditional Protestant hostility both to contemporary Roman Catholicism and to those historical periods that had been perceived as Catholic, especially the patristic era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFathers of the churchvStudy and teachingzUnited StatesxHistoryx19th century. 0aFathers of the churchvStudy and teaching. 0aFathers of the churchxStudy and teachingzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aProtestant theological seminarieszUnited StatesxHistoryx19th century. 0aProtestant theological seminarieszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aTheologyvStudy and tea